# GSAP Animation

Authored from GSAP's official documented patterns. GSAP and all its plugins (ScrollTrigger, SplitText, Flip, MorphSVG, Draggable, etc.) are free as of the v3.13 / Webflow era. Verify current API against gsap.com/docs before relying on version-specific details.

## Core model

GSAP animates any numeric property of any object — DOM, SVG, canvas, WebGL, JS objects. Two building blocks:

- **Tween** — a single animation: `gsap.to(target, vars)`, `gsap.from()`, `gsap.fromTo()`, `gsap.set()`.
- **Timeline** — a container that sequences tweens with precise relative timing.

```js
// Tween: animate TO these values.
gsap.to(".box", { x: 300, rotation: 360, duration: 1, ease: "power2.out" });

// Timeline: sequence with position parameters.
const tl = gsap.timeline({ defaults: { duration: 0.6, ease: "power2.out" } });
tl.from(".title", { y: 40, opacity: 0 })
  .from(".subtitle", { y: 20, opacity: 0 }, "-=0.3")   // overlap 0.3s
  .from(".cta", { scale: 0.9, opacity: 0 }, "<");        // start with previous
```

## Position parameters (timeline timing)

The third argument to a timeline method controls when it starts: absolute time (`1.5`), relative to end (`"-=0.3"` overlaps, `"+=0.5"` gaps), `"<"` (start of previous tween), `">"` (end of previous), or a label. This is the heart of orchestrated sequences.

## Easing

Easing carries personality. `power1`–`power4` (with `.in`/`.out`/`.inOut`), `back`, `elastic`, `expo`, `circ`, `sine`, `steps()`, and custom `CustomEase`. Default to `power2.out` for entrances, `power2.in` for exits. Avoid `linear` for UI (mechanical feel) except continuous loops.

## ScrollTrigger

The plugin for scroll-driven motion. Register before use: `gsap.registerPlugin(ScrollTrigger)`.

```js
gsap.to(".panel", {
  xPercent: -100,
  ease: "none",
  scrollTrigger: {
    trigger: ".container",
    start: "top top",
    end: "+=2000",
    scrub: 1,        // tie progress to scrollbar (1 = 1s catch-up smoothing)
    pin: true,       // lock the trigger while animating
  },
});
```

Key options: `trigger`, `start`/`end` (`"top center"`, `"+=500"`), `scrub` (link to scroll position), `pin` (lock element during the scroll range), `toggleActions` (play/pause/resume/reverse on enter/leave), `markers: true` for debugging. Use `pin` for sections that lock while content reveals; `scrub` for parallax and progress-tied reveals.

## Common premium patterns

**Staggered reveal:** `gsap.from(".item", { y: 30, opacity: 0, stagger: 0.08 })` — `stagger` can be a number or object (`{ each, from: "center", grid: "auto" }`).

**Text animation:** SplitText splits headlines into chars/words/lines for cascading entrances. Always restore and respect reduced motion.

**Horizontal scroll journey:** pin a container, translate `xPercent` of an inner track driven by `scrub`.

**Magnetic / pointer interactions:** use `gsap.quickTo()` for high-frequency pointer-follow updates (far cheaper than creating tweens per mousemove).

## Performance & hygiene

- Animate `transform` (`x`, `y`, `scale`, `rotation`) and `opacity` — GSAP routes `x`/`y` to `translate3d` for compositing. Avoid animating layout properties.
- Use `gsap.context()` (or the React `useGSAP()` hook) to scope animations and auto-clean on unmount — prevents leaks in SPA/React.
- Batch many similar ScrollTriggers with `ScrollTrigger.batch()`.
- Call `ScrollTrigger.refresh()` after layout changes that affect positions.
- **Reduced motion:** gate non-essential motion. `gsap.matchMedia()` with `"(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)"` to provide a calm/instant variant.

```js
const mm = gsap.matchMedia();
mm.add("(prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference)", () => {
  // full motion here; auto-reverted when the query stops matching
});
```

## Framework notes

React/Next: use the official `@gsap/react` `useGSAP()` hook — handles context scoping and cleanup. Pair with Lenis for smooth-scroll inertia under ScrollTrigger. Next.js: animations run client-side only (`"use client"`).

## Load choreography (from hero reps)

- Entrance sequences run on ONE delayed timeline. The opening beat of
  stillness is a named value: `hero-beat: 2s` before anything moves.
  (Authored: doubled from the common 1s — stillness reads as confidence.)
- Sequential tweens on a load timeline OVERLAP via position parameters
  (default `"-=0.5"`). Queued motion reads mechanical; braided motion
  reads choreographed.
- Clip-path reveals: animate polygon points from a fully closed position
  to the full rectangle. Pair `duration: 1` with `ease: "circ.out"` for
  a confident pop. Author start/end shapes at bennettfeely.com/clippy.
- Character rises: `SplitText.create(target, { type: "chars" })`, then
  `.from(split.chars, { yPercent: 200, stagger: 0.02, ease: "power2.out" })`
  inside an `overflow-hidden` wrapper. The wrapper is the letterbox —
  without it the trick is exposed.

## Scroll-linked transforms

- Scroll-driven motion lives on its OWN timeline with
  `scrollTrigger: { scrub: true }` — never mixed onto the load timeline.
  Load = theater (plays once). Scroll = puppet (user drives it).
- Container tilts: `rotate` + `scale` + `yPercent` on the section
  container, `start: "1% top"`, `end: "bottom top"`.

## Pre-states are markup's job

- Any element that animates IN must start in its pre-state in the markup
  (`opacity-0` class, closed clip-path inline style) — never set the
  pre-state from JS. If the animation is deleted, the page must fail
  visible-but-unstyled, not invisible.
  (Learned: an `opacity-1` typo silently killed the fade.)
